model_explanation: the prosodic focus is on "Ellen." This means Sam did not give grapes to anyone besides Ellen. S2 says Sam gave Ellen oranges, which contradicts the focus interpretation that Ellen only got grapes.

the prosodic focus is on "Ellen." This means Sam did not give apples to anyone except Ellen. S2 talks about Rob receiving apples, which is unrelated and doesn't follow from the first sentence nor directly contradicts it. So they are independent.

the prosodic focus is on "Mary." This means Sam didn't give oranges to anyone except Mary. If Sam only gave Mary oranges, it naturally follows that he didn’t give her bananas. Thus S2 is entailed by S1.
the focus is on "Mary," meaning no one else besides Mary got oranges. S2 contradicts that by saying Sam also gave oranges to Tom.
the focus is on "Mary." It means that no one other than Mary got oranges. Therefore, S2, which says Sam didn’t give oranges to Tom, follows naturally and is entailed.
the focus is on "Mary," meaning Mary only received grapes and nothing else. The second sentence says Mary also received apples, which contradicts the focus interpretation.
the prosodic focus is on "Sue." That means only Sue got apples, and no one else did. S2 contradicts this by saying Mary also got apples.
the focus is on "Bill," meaning only Bill received oranges and nothing else. S2 says Bill got bananas too, contradicting the exclusive nature of the first sentence.
the focus is on "Ellen," meaning Ellen only received bananas and nothing else. S2 contradicts that by stating Ellen also got grapes.
the prosodic focus is on "Tom," meaning only Tom got bananas and not anything else. S2, which says Sam didn’t give Tom oranges, is consistent with and entailed by S1.
